Introduction

PerformanceAnalytics is a library designed to evaluate the performance and risk of financial assets/funds. The claimed goal of the package is to make it simple to ask and answer questions. There are some really useful features of the package that dont require you to write a large amount of code. You can do most of the things showing in the package with Base R, but it makes some calculations really simple. We will work through a few of them.

So how is this different from Quantmod? Quantmod is a great tool for quickly putting together a basic trading model and the nice looking charts. When it was released, one of the great benefits of the package was the ability to download data directly from the Yahoo or Google API. This has been supplanted by Quandl (you can find my writeup here), which greatly enhances the ability to download the necessary data. I would say that the benefits of PerformanceAnalytics are some basic functionality to be able to analyze the risk/return characteristics of stocks, or especially as to the performance of a fund manager. There isnt really any new functionality here; it is just a wrapper to be able to compute a number of things (such as alpha and beta) and generate plots.

Installing and Loading Data

So, to get started we need to install and load the packages.

install.packages("PerformanceAnalytics")
library(PerformanceAnalytics)
library(Quandl) #for downloading our data

And, lets go ahead and download some data to work with. What I am downloading here are the S&P 500 Index as our benchmark along with some Merrill Lynch Bond Indices. (I know, thats not a good choice of a benchmark for bond funds, but this is to illustrate the usage) You will notice that we have collapsed this to monthly and transformed into returns. Data for the package MUST be in return format. Otherwise, the package will spit out some garbage; I had some issues with the package initially because of this. Because the S&P500 data has a longer time series, I want to also drop out all the observations that have a missing value.

Quandl.api_key("W8WDsBsiE9HFJzySzLQ3")
data <- Quandl(c("YAHOO/INDEX_GSPC.6", #S&P 500 Index
                 "ML/EMCTRI", #Emerging Markets Corporate Bond Total Return Index 
                 "ML/AATRI", #US AA Total Return Index
                 "ML/BBTRI", #US BB Bond Total Return Index
                 "ML/CCCTRI"),  #US CCC Bond Total Return Index
               collapse = "monthly", #Making into monthly data
               transform = "rdiff", #converting into return data
               type = "xts") #And making into an xts object
names(data) <- c("SP500", "EMCTRI", "MLBBTRI", "AATRI", "CCCTRI") #Renaming to make easier to read

Because the S&P500 data has a longer time series, I want to also drop out all the observations that have a missing value.

Now, we can use one of the basic R plotting functions with ts.plot(). This generates a messy plot and requires a fair amount of code to write it, in addition to the fact that there isnt much information contained.

ts.plot(data, col=c("black", "red", "blue", "green", "purple"), main="A messy plot")       #The plot
legend("bottomleft", names(data), col=c("black", "red", "blue", "green", "purple"), lty=1) #And the legend

Charts with PerformanceAnalytics

We can use the below methods to generate an overlaid chart - chart.BarVaR() - or on separate charts - charts.BarVaR(). This tells us our Value-at-Risk and we can actually pass as an argument which method we want to use. You can find another reference here.

chart.BarVaR(data)

charts.BarVaR(data,
              methods="HistoricalVaR")

We can also plot the cumulative returns and the drawdowns overlaid on each other.

chart.CumReturns(data)

chart.Drawdown(data)

Now, this is pretty neat and all, but what you probably wanted was a quick way to get right into it. We put all of this into one chart with the charts.PerformanceSummary() like below.

charts.PerformanceSummary(data)

Plus, there are some other neat plotting functions like:

chart.Boxplot(data)

chart.RiskReturnScatter(data, Rf = .02/12, add.sharpe = TRUE, add.boxplots = TRUE)

chart.Histogram(data[,2])  #Shows the tail risk pretty clear, we call a single column

chart.Histogram(data[,2], methods = c("add.risk", "add.centered")) #And why VaR is not as effective at controlling the substantial downside risk

CAPM Calculations

There are some other pretty good tools for computing CAPM alphas and betas. We can compute these factors to see if a particular manager has acheived alpha(negative or postive). In the below calculations, we will be working with individual stock data - specifically Apple, Microsoft, Tesla, and GE, along with the S&P 500 as the benchmark/market return. One nice feature PerformanceAnalytics does not have is the ability to compute the Fama-French factor loadings. While its not that difficult to compute them, it would be nice - Fama-French Calculations
So, we start off by downloading the data in monthly returns and xts, then removing any NAs.

stockData <- Quandl(c("WIKI/AAPL.11", "WIKI/MSFT.11", "WIKI/TSLA.11", "WIKI/GE.11", "YAHOO/INDEX_GSPC.6"), collapse="monthly", transform="rdiff", type="xts")
stockData <- na.omit(stockData)
names(stockData) <- c("AAPL", "MSFT", "TSLA", "GE", "SP500")

We now can compute the betas on each of the stocks using CAPM.beta() and CAPM.alpha(). The first required argument is the vector(s) you are computing on, second column is the vector of the benchmmark, and the third being the risk-free rate. For this example we are using a 2% annual rate and insert ( Rf=0.02/12 ) divided by 12 to adjust it to a monthly risk-free rate. One thing you will need to watch out for when calculating these is that they do not display the statistical significance. This isnt a huge issue for Beta, but it definitely is for computing alpha. We dont know if the positive or negative value displayed by CAPM.alpha() is statistically different from zero.

stocks <- stockData[,1:4]
mkt <- stockData[,5]
CAPM.beta(stocks, mkt, Rf=0.02/12)
##                  AAPL     MSFT      TSLA       GE
## Beta: SP500 0.9875436 1.009824 0.6204877 1.306023
CAPM.alpha(stocks, mkt, Rf=0.02/12)
##                     AAPL        MSFT       TSLA          GE
## Alpha: SP500 0.008900823 0.006052579 0.03880699 0.002232203

We can also compute the slope of the Capital Markets Line (CML) and the risk premium. What this risk premium measures shows is how much return we would actually be gaining above the risk-free rate. If this value is negative, it means that we shouldnt have been holding this asset as there was not enough compensation for the risk taken.

CAPM.CML.slope(mkt, Rf=0.02/12)
##                                     SP500
## Capital Market Line Slope: SP500 0.241552
CAPM.RiskPremium(stockData[,1:4], Rf=0.02/12)
##                              AAPL       MSFT       TSLA         GE
## Risk Premium (Rf=0.2%) 0.01753451 0.01488106 0.04423166 0.01365023

We are also able to summarise the above information much quicker by calculating a couple tables.

While the CAPM factors are not perfect, there are some other factors outside of standard deviation we can use to calculate the downside risk. Of course, the reason we want to calculate the downside risk is that volatility on the upside is not of concern - we really are concerned about what we could lose. Below are two ways to calculate this downside risk.

#Calculating Downside risk
SemiDeviation(stockData[,1])
##                      AAPL
## Semi-Deviation 0.04980317
#A more general case Sortino and Price(1994)
DownsideDeviation(stockData[,1], MAR=0)
## [1] 0.03963306

And, we can naturally create a table to show us all the relevant information

table.DownsideRisk(stockData, Rf=0.03/12) #Rf is optional
##                                 AAPL    MSFT    TSLA      GE   SP500
## Semi Deviation                0.0498  0.0427  0.1011  0.0403  0.0256
